<div id="review_806408157" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/806408157" />
    <a title="Alej" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14880227-alej"><img alt="Alej" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1381606422p2/14880227.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/806408157?book_show_action=true">Dec 31, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alej" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alej" href="/user/show/14880227-alej">Alej</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14880227-alej?shelf=books-i-couldn-t-finish">books-i-couldn-t-finish</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14880227-alej?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14880227-alej?shelf=science">science</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer806408157" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8737693033394133843">I brought this book to work with me during the incredibly slow weeks of the holiday season. The book was repetitive, full of purple prose, and overly sentimental about &quot;science&quot; in a way that reminded me of my parochial school days. I had expected a good book explaining stuff about astronomy, science, whathaveyou, but it was mostly emotional pandering to atheists who think they&apos;re morally/intellectually superior to non-atheists. There was a whole lot of nothing for a couple hundred pages that ca</span>
  <span id="freeText8737693033394133843" style="display:none">I brought this book to work with me during the incredibly slow weeks of the holiday season. The book was repetitive, full of purple prose, and overly sentimental about "science" in a way that reminded me of my parochial school days. I had expected a good book explaining stuff about astronomy, science, whathaveyou, but it was mostly emotional pandering to atheists who think they're morally/intellectually superior to non-atheists. There was a whole lot of nothing for a couple hundred pages that can be summarised with: "The world and universe is super great and I don't understand why religion is a thing." Which, like, congrats, I s'pose. You could've just said it once instead of wanking over it for a million pages. It was kind of silly, which was pretty sad, seeing as I'm a huge fan of some of Sagan's other works and his show, "Cosmos." </span>
  <a data-text-id="8737693033394133843" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
