<div id="review_3735757875" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3735757875" />
    <a title="João Dias" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23395540-jo-o-dias"><img alt="João Dias" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1377461550p2/23395540.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3735757875?book_show_action=true">Jan 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="João Dias" class="user" itemprop="url" name="João Dias" href="/user/show/23395540-jo-o-dias">João Dias</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23395540-jo-o-dias?shelf=science">science</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3735757875" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13653551465904208108">Carl Sagan is one of my favourite Science authors and I think this is one of his best works, I would only place Cosmos higher in the list. The book has some years already, was released in 1997, but it doesn’t feel outdated at all. You just end up wishing that Carl Sagan was still around to describe and tell you about the advancements that were made in the past 24 years since the book was written.<br/> <br/>The title is self-explanatory, a book about Space and Humanity, about how we got where we are and to</span>
  <span id="freeText13653551465904208108" style="display:none">Carl Sagan is one of my favourite Science authors and I think this is one of his best works, I would only place Cosmos higher in the list. The book has some years already, was released in 1997, but it doesn’t feel outdated at all. You just end up wishing that Carl Sagan was still around to describe and tell you about the advancements that were made in the past 24 years since the book was written.<br> <br>The title is self-explanatory, a book about Space and Humanity, about how we got where we are and to where we might go in the future. It touches a large range of subjects, from History to Anthropology to Philosophy to Astronomy to Engineering, all brought together to help painting this vision of what could be the human future in Space.<br> <br>The title and the inspiration for the book come from this picture, took by Voyager 1 in 1990, while the ship was speeding away from the Sun at 64 000 kilometers per hour, 6 billion kilometers away from Earth. From this distant vantage point, the Earth is just that small, barely visible speck of dust “suspended in a sunbeam”, a pale blue dot.<br> <br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1599234441i/30061837._SY540_.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>It’s a great book that really inspires a sense of awe about the Universe and about what Humans can achieve.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13653551465904208108" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


